column168: ON JULY 10, 2017 AT 2:15 P.M., CRIMSON RENEWABLE ENERGY (CRE) EXPERIENCED A METHANOL TRANSFER HOSE FAILURE. THE HOSE WAS HOOKED UP FROM THE RAIL-CAR TO THE INBOUND METHANOL LINE TO CRE’S TANK. AS AN EMPLOYEE WAS CHECKING TO ENSURE THE VALVES ON THE INBOUND METHANOL LINE WERE OPEN, OTHER PERSONNEL WITNESSED THE HOSE BEGIN TO BUBBLE AND BLISTER IMMEDIATELY UPSTREAM OF THE FIRST VALVE ON THE METHANOL LINE, WHICH WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THE HOSE BURST OPEN, RELEASING METHANOL TOWARDS THE EAST. THE HOSE HAS BEEN ANALYZED TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE RUPTURE.  ORDERS WERE IMMEDIATELY GIVEN TO EVACUATE AND ALL PERSONNEL AND CONTRACTORS REPORTED TO THE MUSTER AREA. APPROPRIATE AUTHORIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND KERN COUNTY PUBLIC HEALTH SERVICES DEPARTMENT ARRIVED. THE SITE WAS MONITORED UNTIL DEEMED SAFE.
column169: EXPONENT, INC. (“EXPONENT”), AN INDEPENDENT EXPERT FIRM, WAS RETAINED TO ASCERTAIN THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE HOSE RUPTURE. EXPONENT’S COMPLETE REPORT IS ATTACHED HERTO. AFTER ANALYZING THE HOSE AT ISSUE, AND REVIEWING RECORDS PERTAINING TO THE RAIL CAR TO WHICH THE HOSE WAS CONNECTED, AS WELL AS CRE’S PROCEDURES AND OTHER EQUIPMENT, EXPONENT DETERMINED THAT THE SOLE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS A FAULTY HOSE. SPECIFICALLY, EXPONENT FOUND THAT THE LEAK” WAS THE RESULT OF A TEAR IN THE HOSE,” AND THAT (T)HE HOSE LINER EXHIBITS DEEP, HELICAL GROOVES WHICH APPEAR TO HAVE DEVELOPED DURING THE MANUFACTURING PROCESS.” EXPONENT REPORT AT 3-4. EXPONENT FOUND NO EVIDENCE THAT CRE FAILED TO PROPERLY MAINTAIN THE HOSE OR ANY OTHER EQUIPMENT USED DURING THE INCIDENT. EXPONENT FOUND THAT CRE DID NOT OVER-PRESSURIZE THE HOSE, AS A REVIEW OF CRE’S PROCEDURES AND EQUIPMENT” INDICATES THAT IT WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN POSSIBLE FOR [CRE] TO PRESSURIZE THE METHANOL HOSE ABOVE ITS 200 PSI RATED WORKING PRESSURIZE WHILE OFFLOADING METHANOL FROM THE RAIL CAR.” EXPONENT REPORT A 4. THE REPORT ALSO NOTES THAT THE RAIL CAR AT ISSUE WAS PROPERLY EQUIPPED WITH TWO PRESSURE RELIEF VALVES, WHICH HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY TESTED AND FOUND TO BE OPERATING CORRECTLY. EXPONENT REPORT AT 2.  ALSO ATTACHED HERETO IS A SUMMARY OF THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS CRE HAS TAKEN IN RESPONSE TO THIS INCIDENT (“ATTACHMENT A”).

This incident did not require a special switching move.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: When the WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector was doing an inbound inspection of cars on an adjacent track, he heard car SHQX 51450 hissing from on top the car and an odor was evident.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I went out to the yard and inspected the car and found that the vapor valve handle was loose and the valve plug was not even hand tight.  I tightened the valve handle to see if the leak would stop and it did so I tightened the valve plug and released the car for service.  I removed seal #10669 from the manway lid but did not install a new seal.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: On July 03, 2017, during unloading operations terminal personnel discovered a damaged (1)10-gallon poly pail of UN1866 Resin "Methyl Methacrylate" damaged from improper preparation for transit. Approximately 0.5-gallon released to the trailer floor. The terminal personnel contained and cleaned the release by utilizing granular absorbents. The damaged pail and impacted debris were properly overpacked and staged in OS&D.

After investigation, it was concluded that the 5 gallon pail had slid off the skid during transit and was punctured by a nail on the trailer floor.  Upon discovering the release absorbent material was used to collect released material. The damaged pail and absorbent material was placed into an overpack for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This damaged may have been prevented by properly blocking and bracing the skid of pails for transit. Proper inspection of the trailer floor for protruding nails may also have prevented this release. This incident may be used as an example in future dock meetings to illustrate the importance of properly blocking and bracing freight.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported a strong odor coming from tank car UTLX213404.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the odor was a vapor leak from the sample line valve.  The valve was found to be in the open position and the plug was less than tool tight.  The sample line valve was closed and the plug tightened.  The car was secured and released for transportation.

Driver of tractor trailer suffered a medical condition.  The unit traveled to right side hitting guide rail and riding down the same until guide rail ended.  Unit then continued through a grassy area and then into a wooded area coming to rest upright.  The freight in the unit was pushed forward due to the force of stop and a pallet that crushed impelled the container thus breaching the same.  The breach in the container was approximately 4"x2" with the wood remaining impelled into the container until the container was pumped out.  The accident occurred at approximately 0030 hours and final pump out occurred around 0330.  The material was contained within the trailer with exception of about 5-10 gallon which leaked onto a rocky area.  All this area was padded and cleaned per requirements set forth by PA DEP and responding contractor.
column169: Due to the circumstances surrounding the events leading up to the breach of the container, it is in my opinion that nothing further could be done to prevent what occurred.  The force of the uncontrolled stop is what resulted in all aspects of freight damage.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

AFTER NEUTRALIZING THE SPILLED PRODUCT, I TOOK THE PACKAGE BACK TO PSC FOR PROCESSING. I REFERRED TO THE WASTE DISPOSAL CHART FOR DISPOSITION OF THE PACKAGE. AFTER WHICH, I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

column168: When the Brewster Yard Car Switch Crew was moving car NATX 37862, they noticed some liquid dripping from the bottom of it when they coupled into it.  They said they also noticed a vapor coming from it.  They called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came out to investigate and found that the liquid dripping from the car was just water.  I did notice an odor and then used my gas meter to find that the vapor was coming from the gasket at the base of the liquid valve on top the car.  The gasket between the flanged surfaces of the valve and the car was leaking vapor.  I could not get it to stop leaking.  I called the shipper to contacted Sunpro to come out and replace the gasket and then pressure test the car.

column168: When the Brewster Yard switch crew was switching, they noticed an odor coming from car NATX 300311.  They called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I investigated and found that liquid was coming from the valve plug on top the liquid valve.  The valve was in the closed position.  I depressurized the car to get the leak to stop.  I then took the valve plug off and opened the valve to relive the pressure and to get the liquid off the top of the valve.  I then installed thread sealant on the plug threads and reinstalled the plug and then sealed up the car.  The liquid was leaking through the defective seat of the ball valve.  I was able to secure the car until the car owner could make arrangements to get a contractor out to make permanent repairs.  On July 19, 2017, Markwest had Sunpro come to our Brewster rail yard and replace the defective liquid valve and then bubble test the car.  I removed old seal 1383406 from the bread box lid and Sunpro installed new seal 1380658.
column169: I do not think this defect would have been noticed during loading.

column168: When the Brewster yard switch crew was working in the yard, they noticed an odor coming from GATX 214840.  They reported to the Brewster Yardmaster who then called me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  When I came out to inspect, I found that there was liquid leaking from the plug on top of the liquid ball valve on top the car.  The valve was closed and still leaking.  I depressurized the car and removed the plug.  I put new thread sealant on the plug threads and reinstalled the plug.  The leak stopped.  The valve was defective.  I had the car sent to the shop so final repairs could be made by a contractor.  Markwest had Sunpro come out on July 19, 2017 and install a new ball valve and then bubble test the car.  I removed old seal 0358833 from the bread box lid and Sunpro installed new seal 1380587 and then the car was released for service.
column169: I do not think this would have been noticed upon loading of the car.

column168: At approximately 1730 on July 14, 2007 a Veolia employee observed a colored puddle under the trailer, and reported it to the Veolia Shift Supervisor. The employee placed floor dry and a spill pallet under the trailer. The Veolia response team reviewed the manifests for the trailer and approved a verbal Heath and Safety Plan including Tychem 2000 and supplied air for entry and identification of the leaking container. Responder entered the trailer and retrieved the label from the leaking container. The container was leaking from a drum failure on its side believed to be created by corrosion.      EH&S reviewed the WIP for chemical constituents. RQ of the material was confirmed to be 100lbs. On review of the WIP it was decided to upgrade to Tychem 4000 with supplied air for working with the leaking container. The trailer was unloaded and a sample taken from the leaking container to confirm an RQ was not met. The drum was overpacked and free liquid cleaned up with floor dry.
column169: Veolia employees were retrained on pre-transport container integrity inspections.

column168: Tampa, FL – 7/09/2017 – RCRX 2704 – Hydrochloric Acid        On 7/09/2017 at 2000, personnel in the CSXT Uceta Yard, Tampa, FL discovered RCRX 2704, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric acid, leaking from the loading / unloading liquid closure flange due to two corroded and broken nut and bolt assemblies.  The car was isolated and the shipper Reagent Chemical & Research, Inc., the Florida Department of Environmental Protection (report number 2017-5136), and the NRC (report number 1183583) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2017-07-09-00045.  SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the loading / unloading liquid closure flange.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Kevin Callais, phone number 281-404-9728).  Contractor personnel replaced the broken nut / bolt assemblies.  The shipper hired SPSI to replace the liquid education line and put new top fitting closure flanges, bolts, and gaskets, and bubble leak tested the car.  During further inspection by the shipper, the gasket on the closure flange was missing.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.    Cause Code: 104

column168: Air Products driver was returning to home terminal after a delivery. He heard a loud noise at rear of trailer. Driver pulled off highway to safe location to investigate. The stainless steel flex pipe supplying the inlet side of the LCO2 load out pump had catastrophically failed causing the pump to twist out of position toward front of trailer. It damaged the bottom of trailer skin and pump frame. No injuries and no third party damage.
column169: The flex hose failure was the result of an overpressure of the line due to liquid CO2 not properly being cleared. A main contributing factor was the lack of relief protection in the section of piping between 2 block valves.  Active coaching and discussions about this incident will be and are taking place during mandatory safety meetings. All fleet trailers have been inspected to review proper thermal relief valve placement. Further review of the "flex hoses" are taking place as well.

column168: At approximately 1500 hours on July 8, 2017 inspectors in the BNSF Barstow, CA trainyard identified tank car GBRX 700255 leaking diesel fuel from the combination housing at the top of the car.  BNSF hazmat responder evaluated and determined that the threaded nipple which the liquid valve sits on, had come loose allowing product to leak from the base of the threaded nipple.  The nipple was loose approximately 1/2 turn.  Responder loosened the valve/nipple assembly, applied additional teflon tape, and tightened the assembly which stopped the leak.  No release to environment occurred and wetness on tank car was mopped up.  Shipper obtained OTMA-3 and no further action was required.

column168: The trailer was discovered to be leaking during a pre-trip inspection at the Veolia 10 day in-transit facility located in Phoenix, AZ. The area was immediately cordoned off and efforts began to contain and clean-up the released material.     Upon further inspection, it was discovered that the IBC was ruptured at the bottom of the container which resulted in most of the contents being released during the event.    Liquids remaining within the breached container were transferred to an appropriate DOT container for shipment to the ultimate disposal site. The empty breached container was cut up for disposal and containerized along with the debris generated during the clean-up. Containers of other waste materials on the trailer were not damaged during the release and were transferred to a clean trailer. The trailer was secured and removed from the Veolia 10-Day Yard to the MP Environmental Yard for decontamination. A bob cat style excavator was used to remove from 1 inch to 3 inches of soil in the area under and behind the trailer. Potentially contaminated soil was collected in a roll off bin and is currently in temporary storage at the Veolia 10-Day Yard. The release was localized to the area directly under and behind the trailer. The material did not penetrate the soil greater than 2 -3 inches and was clearly discernable by the staining of the soil and gravel. Based on analytical results received, additional excavation to a depth of 1 foot of the spill area is planned to begin on July 25, 2017.
column169: Additional training with employees responsible for the packaging of IBC containers, containing hydrogen peroxide solutions >40 but less 60 percent to assure the container has a vented bung. Notification also to the shipper of the material.

SMEAR RESULTS WERE OBTAINED FOR THE 56 DRUMS INVOLVED IN THE SHIPMENT. REMOVABLE BETA ON THE LEAKING DRUM POST DECON WAS FOUND TO MEASURE 337.95 DPM/100 CM2. THIS EQUIVALENT TO 34 DPM/CM2 ONCE A 10% SMEAR EFFICIENCY IS APPLIED. DOT LIMITS FOR REMOVABLE BETA CONTAMINATION ARE 240 DPM/CM2 PER 49CFR173.443 TABLE 9.     SPILLED MATERIAL (LESS THAN 25 GRAMS) WAS RECOVERED AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED. IN ADDITION, THE INSIDE AND OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS MONITORED FOR CONTAMINATION. THE TRAILER MET DOT LIMITS FOR FREE RELEASE, AND WAS THUS ALLOWED TO DEPART THE CONSIGNEE’S SITE.

column168: An SK Driver picked up 3 Flexbins from a customer site and delivered them back to the SK Branch.  The next afternoon while sitting in Temporary Storage one of the Flex Bins side walls collapsed causing a small amount of HazWaste Paint to leak from a 1 gallon plastic container that was placed inside the Flexbin.  It was determined that the cap from the plastic container came off when the side walls failed. It was also determine that the sidewalls showed signs of water damage possibly causing the walls to collapse.  The employee's immediately cleaned up the area using sorbent material, and the material inside the Flex Bin was re-packaged into a Lined Flexbin and the clean up material was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: The Customer was reminded to store all Fiberboard Flexbins inside a protected area so that they would not be exposed to the elements. The Driver was also reminded to inspect all containers for integrity issues prior to accepting & placing them on a company vehicle.

column168: On 07/21/17 at 2323 hours personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered GATX72396, a loaded tank car of hydrochloric acid leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper PVS CHLORALKALI INC was notified. Specialized Professional Services Inc. (SPSI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found chemically deteriorated bolts on the liquid line valve blinde flange causing the release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper John Bennett (PVS) at 440-668-9379. Contractor personnel applied C-clamps securing the release and neutralized and excavated all released materials and impacted ballast/ soil.  The shipper (PVS) dispatched ResCar and they replaced the bolts and ensured the car was back in compliance. The car was released.        NAR Cause Code: 245 – liquid line blind flange (no valve)    2(5+5+1) x (2+0) = 44 NARRI     New Orleans, LA – 07/22/17 – GATX72396 – Hydrochloric Acid

column168: On July 28, 2017, XPO Logistics (LDA Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide, 8, PG II, (PRO#714162190) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (3196336) from a city pickup, when terminal personnel discovered a pallet to be tipped over due to improper loading. The caller indicated that there are approximately 15 boxes of 33.3 ounce containers to have been damaged (495 ounces). It is unknown in the exact amount released at this time. Contractor has identified the product as "Instant Power Plumbing and Drain Solutions- Hair Clog Remover." There are boxes containing 4-gallon plastic jugs. Contractor is sorting through the boxes to locate the leaking jug.Contractor found (1) 4-gallon poly jug that had a pinhole in the bottom. Contractor indicated that approximately 2 gallons of product was released from that jug.Contractor also indicated that there are several jugs with loose caps. Caps were tightened and placed onto a pallet. Contractor has re-palletized freight and shrink-wrapped skid. Contractor estimated approximately 3 gallons lost in total. Contractor utilized Color safe to neutralize release. Contractor generated (1) 55-gallon drum of the damaged jug with product and (1) 55-gallon poly drum of neutralized cleanup debris for waste. All waste was staged on site for XPO to manage disposition.

Simple Green Solution was applied to the trailer floor to mitigate the smell from the material. column168: A 40 yard roll-off box was staged in a 10 day transfer facility containment area. Upon loading of box, as it was lifted onto the transport vehicle, the  sludge material flowed to the rear of the box, overtopping the rear gate and spilling into the containment area. The material had phase separated  during transport releasing free liquid. An internal response team was dispatched to remediate the area. Crew donned proper PPE and assessed the site.  Site was remediated effectively and all waste was containerized compliantly. Waste was shipped to final destination disposal facility without further  incident. Utah DEQ notified and state report #13040 was generated by operator Chris Martin.
column169: Corporate and local management proceeded with investigative conference calls. Direct communication and guidance with onsite personnel loading the  boxes, educating them on what is acceptable material to haul in roll-off containers. Educated driving teams on proper pre trip container inspections to  prevent further incidents. Executive management staffs of both motor carrier and generator, actively worked together to create a new operating  procedure involving adding more solidifying agents to ensure waste stream remains solid in transport, thus nullifying phase shifting. Suspended current  disposal profile and required generator re-certify waste stream as a new profile using more solidifying agents.

column168: Memphis, TN. It was reported that shortly following a pickup from the shipper, multiple cylinders of UN1078 Refrigerant gas (Fluorinated Hydrocarbons) tipped over in the trailer and are hissing and appear to be releasing gas. column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: The driver, after successfully loading all but one polyethylene drums with a drum cart, had a drum develop a slow leak from the bottom while loading it onto the truck for shipment. The released waste impacted the trucks lift gate and concrete containment pad; no soil, water or storm drains were impacted. The driver immediately notified facility personnel, who donned the correct PPE and assessed the situation. The drum with the release was pumped off into a new UN spec rated polyethylene drum, and correctly labeled and marked for transportation to the final destination facility. The waste generated from the clean up was placed in a salvage drum along with the punctured drum, and placed into the appropriate waste stream for later disposal.    It was found that the most probable cause for this release was due to prior damage/abrasion to this drum which was aggravated by the drum cart.    This release was reported to the state of Colorado, however the volume released fell below the reportable quantity limits for the state and no report number was generated.
column169: The release was discussed with the generator, who has provided facility personnel with additional training on drum inspection. Clean Harbors is also providing additional drum inspection and closure training to our driver who loaded this drum.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On July 30, 2017 at 2059 hours, personnel at CSXT Walbridge Yard discovered GATX 53574, a residue UN 3286, Potassium Hydroxide Isopropanol Organic Pesticide tank car to have an odor coming from protective housing area of the car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Clean Harbors Environmental was notified via the Clean Harbors Emergency Number. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the reclosing pressure relief device had failed. As a preventative measure Sunpro placed plastic over the protective housing to contain any vapors.  A HAZMATHOLD was placed on GATX 53574.    Cause Code: 417 at 2 points  NARRI: 5 (4 + 3 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 70

column168: During a routine site check at a the Clean Harbors' Burton, MI temporary storage facility, a roll off container was found to have a small amount of material coming from the rear door seal leaking onto the ground. The release was immediately reported, and a field services crew, wearing the appropriate personal protective equipment, was summoned to make repairs to the roll off container, clean up the release, and remediate the area. The box was found to have been well tightened, but the rear door seal was found to be defective. Additional sealant was applied affected area, and the roll off box re-tightened, which stopped the leak.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors' Burton, MI facility it was determined the vacuum box was leaking due to the presence of free liquid perhaps from thermal phasing  or condensation . In order to prevent a recurrence, the initial shipper has been notified of the improper preparation and potential presence of free liquids in this solid waste stream, the driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation. In addition, this specific container was placed out of service pending an inspection of the door seal.

column169: CHECK ALL SURROUNDINGS BEFORE MOVING VEHICLES. IN ADDITION THIS WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED IF THE PACKAGE CAR DRIVER UNLOADED THE HAZMAT AT A HAZMAT DROP OFF POINT.

Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car ADMX30192 leaking product from the top of the tank.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the leak was found to be coming from the mounting flange for the liquid line valve.  The leak was the result of the flange being loose due to a broken bolt securing the flange to the tank car.  The leak was stopped by relieving internal pressure on the tank.  The contents of the tank car were transferred into another tank car.

Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car ADMX30611 leaking product from the top of the car.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the leak was found to be from the liquid line.  The leak was the result of the valve being loose on the threaded liquid line nipple.  The valve was tightened to stop the leak.  The car owner applied for an OTMA-1 to move the car to destination for off-loading.

It was reported the driver was performing a pre-inspection of his unit when he noticed a leak coming from his trailer. The driver opened his trailer and was overwhelmed by the fumes and closed the trailer door immediately. A  team was requested to respond to the site for cleanup and remedial actions. It was estimated 30 gallons of UN1760, Hydrofluoric Acid (Acetic anhydride) released to the dirt area underneath the trailer. Contractor responded to the site and transferred the product from the impacted tote into 2-330 gallon poly totes. All three totes were placed back on the trailer. The impacted area beneath the trailer was properly decontaminated and neutralized utilizing color safe. Contractor generated 4-55 gallon poly drums of waste. Contractor transported all generated waste off site for proper disposal.

column168: Carrier completed loading CTMV disconnecting the loading arm from api head on side pipe and product spilled. Carrier found the plunger inside the api head failed to operate.         event 65471-1

The driver of the CTMV failed to secure the dome lid before driving the unit. The unsecured dome lid allowed for approximately 50 gallons of material to slosh out of the unit and spill to the asphalt roadway below. The release stopped once the driver stopped the vehicle. A contractor was dispatched for proper cleanup.

When unloading the drums in question, facility personnel noticed that a drum showed signs of reacting, with a bent and bulging lid. The distortion and bulging of the drum lid was significant enough to allow some reacting waste to seep through the lid and drum ring. The nature of the waste was such that it became a hard foam like substance when its reaction was complete, thus the released waste never got to the ground. Upon discovery, an emergency field services crew was called in and donned the correct personal protective equipment. The crew was able to assess the situation fully, call the generator for detailed instructions on how to stop the monomer reaction, obtain 4-methoxyphenol additive, and fully stabilize the reacting drum. As a precaution, the crew stabilized all the remaining three drums in this shipment.  After this was completed, the damaged drum was placed in salvage drum for continued transportation to the final disposal facility.     There was no additional waste created, as there was no need for cleanup or remediation. The minimal amount of the release did not meet the required threshold for reporting in the state of Pennsylvania.
column169: The generator was made aware of the incident at the time it occurred, and was instrumental in get the situation corrected. They have reviewed the processes and activity that led up to these un-stabilized waste monomer drums being placed into transport; new policies and procedures have been implemented, including the use of a specialized meter to measure the stabilization process. Additional drum inspection retraining was given to the driver who picked up this load from the generator.

column168: ON JULY 10, 2017 AT 2:15 PM CRIMSON RENEWABLE ENERGY (CRE) EXPERIENCED A METHANOL TRANSFER HOSE FAILURE. THE HOSE WAS HOOKED UP FROM THE RAIL-CAR TO THE INBOUND METHANOL LINE TO CRE’S TANK. AS AN EMPLOYEE WAS CHECKING TO ENSURE THE VALVES ON THE INBOUND METHANOL LINES WERE OPEN, OTHER PERSONNEL WITNESSED THE HOSE BEGIN TO BUBBLE AND BLISTER IMMEDIATELY UPSTREAM OF THE FIRST VALVE ON THE METHANOL LINE, WHICH WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THE HOSE BURST OPEN, RELEASING METHANOL TOWARDS THE EAST. THE HOSE IS BEING ANALYZED TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE RUPTURE.     ORDERS WERE IMMEDIATELY GIVEN TO EVACUATE AND ALL PERSONNEL AND CONTRACTORS REPORTED TO THE MUSTER AREA. APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND KERN COUNTY PUBLIC HEALTH SERVICES DEPARTMENT ARRIVED. THE SITE WAS MONITORED UNTIL DEEMED SAFE.
column169: AT THIS TIME, THE HOSE IS BEING ANALYZED TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE RUPTURE, WHICH WILL INFORM WHAT ACTIONS OR RECOMMENDATIONS, IF ANY, CAN BE MADE TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: A 40 yard roll-off box was staged in a 10 day transfer facility containment area. Upon loading of box, as it was lifted onto the transport vehicle, the  sludge material flowed to the rear of the box, overtopping the rear gate and spilling into the containment area. The material had phase separated  during transport releasing free liquid. An internal response team was dispatched to remediate the area. Crew donned proper PPE and assessed the site.  Site was remediated effectively and all waste was containerized compliantly. Waste was shipped to final destination disposal facility without further  incident. Utah DEQ notified and state report #13060 was generated by operator Craig Barnitz.
column169: Corporate and local management proceeded with investigative conference calls. Direct communication and guidance with onsite personnel loading the  boxes, educating them on what is acceptable material to haul in roll-off containers. Educated driving teams on proper pre trip container inspections to  prevent further incidents. Executive management staffs of both motor carrier and generator, actively worked together to create a new operating  procedure involving adding more solidifying agents to ensure waste stream remains solid in transport, thus nullifying phase shifting. Suspended current  disposal profile and required generator re-certify waste stream as a new profile using more solidifying agents.

A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release. The contractor stated that the valve assembly was leaking where it connects to the tote for unknown reasons. The contractor completed a tote transfer for the salvaged material. All generated waste was taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal. The salvaged material was kept on the tractor trailer to be managed by the Landtstar personnel.

column168: THIS PACKAGE CONTAINING A HAZMAT WENT OUT FOR DELIVERY ON 7-31-17. THE PACKAGE WAS EITHER PLACED ON ITS SIDE OR UPSIDE DOWN, AS IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED ALL OVER THE INSIDE OF THE BOX. column168: The tank truck's driver connects to the tank truck the hose to pump to tank over land, the keys are opened, when the discharge is being completed, the coupling sleeve is detached. The sleeve stays in continuous movement (by the pressure) spraying diesel.  The driver promptly closed the valves and removed the spill management kit. Containment procedures were performed to prevent the product from reaching the sewers. In the area there was trench where it was understood that had contained much of the product. Even so, the company was activated for the management of RICLEM environmental emergencies where it identified impact to the sewer near the station, near 6:30 am. He was immediately notified (6:39 am) to Mr. Angel Rodriguez of the Environmental Quality Board.  After evaluation of what happened by RICLEM personnel in the different sewers of the area, product impact was identified in 3 of these and at the mouth of the Torrecilla Lagoon, near the Marina Vista Mar Este.
column169: New process to inspect the hoses was implemented and training's to driver, related to pre-inspection process.

column168: The drum in question was staged in 10 day storage when a forklift operator misjudged his clearance while moving other drums and punctured a drum with the forklift blade. The release was all in a concrete containment area. A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and over-packed the drum into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to clean up the trailer floor. The salvage drum was shipped later without further incident.
column169: The forklift operator was advised to use better care and caution when loading and unloading drums. He is scheduled for retraining, and cannot operate the forklift until this training is completed.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Carrier driver was performing a post-trip inspection and noticed hazmat in the crashbox of the CMTV.  The O-rings on the pressure release valve were found to be deteriorated which kept the valve from fully closing.  The duration of the release occurred no longer than four hours.  The driver and cleanup crew verified that the hazmat release ceases when the CTMV is at a stop.  The pressure release valve O-rings were replaced at a nearby trailer repair facility.  Clean up crew placed absorbent pads on the hazmat and around the pressure release valve.  The Highway Patrol authorized the CTMV to be moved to the repair facility.            Quality Event #65489.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: During routine inspection, facility personnel noticed an active drip coming from a 53' van trailer, which was staged at the 10 day concrete containment pad;  the release impacted the landing gear of the unit and the concrete underneath. No soil, water ways or storm drains were impacted. Facility personnel immediately notified all internal parties and initiated the in-house clean up procedure, utilizing our emergency response team. The facility personnel, wearing the appropriate PPE, mitigated the leak with absorbent material and a bucket. The ER team arrived onsite, donned proper PPE, began the site assessment and entered the trailer. They were able to locate the leaking drum, over-pack the drum, and decontaminate the trailer and site safely. The ER team concluded that the drum had a pin hole near the bottom, thus causing the release. It was also discovered that the UN specification on the drum was too deteriorated/corroded to be read. The waste generated from the clean-up was placed in the over-pack drum, it was properly marked and labeled and sent to the final destination disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver who introduced this drum into transportation was given corrective training in drum closure and inspection, as well as package labeling and marking. The entire branch the driver reports to also addressed these specific topics in a branch meeting. In addition, the 3rd party transporter involved was notified, and asked to give their drivers additional training in drum closure and inspection, as well as package labeling and marking. Additionally, this incident was reported to the waste generator; the importance of choosing and preparing legally compliant packages and drums  was discussed in detail.

column168: ON JULY 10TH 2017 AT ROUGHLY 1030 IN THE MORNING OUR DRIVER PERFORMED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION ON TRAILER 3564. DURING THIS INSPECTION HE SEALED THE TRAILER AND CLOSED ALL OF THE VALVES. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOADING FACILITY THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED AND SENT BACK FOR LOADING. ONCE LOADING WAS COMPLETED THE DRIVER PULLED TO THE SCALE HOUSE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER LOOKED WET. IT WAS FOUND THAT THE WASH OUT CAP WAS LOOSE. THE REAR CAP WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ROUGHLY LESS THAN 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO LEAKED OUT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES TOOK PLACE. WASH OUT CAP WAS PROPERLY TIGHTENED DOWN AND SEALED AND ONCE THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE LOADING FACILITY THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED AND THE TRAILER WAS DELIVERED WITH NO FURTHER ISSUE. THIS FAILURE OCCURRED DUE TO THE DRIVER NOT COMPLETELY TAKING THE CLEAN OUT CAP OFF AND VERIFYING THAT THE CLEAN OUT CAP HAD THE PROPER GASKET IN IT AND WAS CROSS THREADED.
column169: LANGER TRANSPORT ISSUED A MEMO OUT TO THE FLEET ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF A PROPER AND THOROUGH PRE-TRIP INSPECTION SPECIFICALLY NOTATING HOW TO INSPECT THE WASH OUT CAP ON THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO COME BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND BE RETRAINED IN PROPER VEHICLE INSPECTION PROCESSES, PHYSICAL PRE-TRIP TRAINING SPECIFICALLY NOTATING CLEAN-OUT/WASH-OUT CAP PROCEDURES. THE DRIVER WAS ISSUED A WRITTEN WARNING, AND HIS FILE WAS UPDATED. THE LOADING FACILITY CONFIRMED NOTHING FURTHER WAS NEEDED CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT, DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT ISSUE. ONCE ALL RETRAINING WAS COMPLETED, DRIVER WAS RELEASED BACK TO DISPATCH. UPON HIS RELEASE HIS NEXT TRAILER WAS SPOT CHECKED BY SAFETY TO ENSURE ALL OUTLETS PROPERLY SECURED AND SEALED.   WE DO NOT NEED TO CHANGE ANY OF OUR PROCEDURES DUE TO THIS BEING 100% DRIVER ERROR. HAD THE DRIVER FOLLOWED PROPER PROCEDURE, THIS INCIDENT NEVER WOULD HAVE OCCURRED.

column168: GATX 14800 was identified as releasing by the BNSF Railway Mechanical during an outbound inspection in the BNSF Railway Terminal in Barstow, CA on July 17, 2017. column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 7/26/17 at approximately 11:00 MST, yard crews reported an odor associated with the PVCX 13327 tank car at interchange track in Rincon, NM.  The immediate area around the car was isolated and BNSF Hazmat Responders and Contract responders mobilized the following morning to assess and secure the car.  Upon inspection by Hazmat responders, it was noted that there was wetness around the discharge (liquid) line on the car.  Responders vented the tank car through the vapor valve and removed the discharge line cap.  It was identified that the gasket in the liquid line cap had been cut likely due to over-torqueing the fitting.  The gasket was replaced with a temporary Teflon gasket and responders decontaminated the wet surfaces with sodium bicarbonate and water until surfaces had neutral pH.  The car was released and allowed to interchange for switching to destination.
column169: Shipper has been notified of this condition.  Proper loading procedures including torque specifications and replacements schedules for gaskets in appliances should be reviewed and discussed with applicable loading personnel.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: Steve Forler Trucking, a third party transportation vendor, arrived on site to offload their trailer at our facility. Upon arrival, the driver staged his tractor trailer at the 10-day containment pad and immediately noticed an active drip coming from his trailer. The driver notified the Operations Manager and an internal emergency response team was dispatched. The local operation team, donned proper PPE, contained the release with absorbent on the concrete and placed a poly bucket under the active leak. They also re-tracked the trucks path on the property and found no signs of a release on the soil. The ER team arrived on site, donned proper PPE, assessed the site and trailer. It was determined that no soil, water ways or storm/sewer drains were impacted by this release. The ER team entered the trailer and identified the leaking drum, inspected the container and found it was cracked on the bottom of the drum. The ER team thoroughly and safely decontaminated the trailer and site. The waste generated from the response and the damaged drum were safely placed into a UN rated salvage drum, labeled, marked and sent to its final disposal destination without further incident.
column169: An investigation into this release led to clear communication with the generator regarding container selection and inspection when preparing waste for transportation. Communication with the third party transporter regarding similar values, as well as reporting requirements also ensued. All parties involved with the handling of this drum were made aware of the release and subsequently, a branch level stand down was held to counsel on the importance of proper container selection and inspection for transportation.

column168: Univar picked up several corrugated fiberboard boxes of waste from our customer Zippo Manufacturing and transported the waste to Univar's Altoona PA location.  The waste was staged in Altoona for one night then loaded onto a Univar trailer that shuttled from Altoona to Univar's Middletown PA location.  The waste boxes were not leaking when placed on the Altoona to Middletown shuttle.  Upon arriving in Middletown and opening the rear trailer door, Univar employees discovered that one box had leaked about 1-2 gallons onto the floor of the box trailer.  The sealed flap on the one vertical corner of the waste box had ripped apart and the plastic inner liner had been ruptured.  There was free liquid observed in this leaking box (contained within the liner).

column168: AT 17:28 HRS ON 7/10/2017 HAZMAT RESIDUE TANK CAR CCBX 6013 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) WHILE IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) LAREDO TX YARD. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THO CAR. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPOND ERA INSPECTED THE BOV AND BOV PLUG AND FOUND THE PLUG TO BE COMPLETELY OFF AND THE BOV SLIGHTLY OPEN. THE CONTRACTOR CLOSED AND SECURED THE BOV. THE BOV PLUG WAS PUT BACK INTO PLACE AND TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT.FILE NOTE: I TORN 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BAST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILS AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASED AKA PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS, THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSES OF RELEASE AND TO THEN VACILLATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARED THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. ( PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAYS PO BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCES HTTP NAR. AAR. column168: A truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the Bristol, CT transfer facility for offload in order to transfer and consolidate its waste onto a van trailer for transportation to its intended waste disposal facility. While moving it with a fork lift, facility personnel noticed a small leak from the bottom seam of a 55 gallon drum. The minor release was onto secondary concrete containment, no soil or water was impacted.     A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and over packed the leaking drum into a properly rated salvage drum for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The facility floor was also cleaned, and the waste generated by cleanup placed into the appropriate waste stream for disposal.      This release was reported to the CT DEEP 17:18 EST 07/27/2017, #2017-03787  operator# 203.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. There were no apparent signs of rough mishandling of the drum, or of any deterioration. This leads us to conclude the this bottom seam release was likely the result of a manufacturing defect. As a precaution, the driver who originally picked up this drum was given additional drum closure and inspection training.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Failed to Operate
column168: The incident reported herein occurred at an unmanned Hydrochloric Acid Transfer and Storage facility which is owned and operated by Refinery Specialties, Inc. (RSI). The site is leased from a local property owner and has been in operation since 2014. The site consists of two (2) 9,041 gallon-capacity fiberglass reinforced plastic storage tanks, along with an approximately 450 gallon field tank which is used as a water scrubber to control emissions of HCl vapors during loading/unloading operations. All of the tanks sit within a bermed and lined containment area made of native caliche-type soils and gravel. Past practice at this facility has been for the chemical vendor (Reagent Chemical) to perform chemical deliveries without RSI personnel present on-site. On the date of the incident, a new delivery driver for Reagent who was unfamiliar with the site arrived to offload a 5,000 gallon shipment of 32% HCl. He was operating Tractor# 635980 and Trailer #634 when the incident occurred. The BOL did not indicate which of the two tanks was to be filled. The driver attempted to verify which of the two tanks was empty using level gauges but experienced some difficulty; he had been instructed to check sight glasses and unload into the tank with the lowest level, but the valve to one of the sight glasses was closed. After eventually confirming which tank had sufficient freeboard, he connected the transfer hoses and began transferring acid from the tanker to what he believed to be the empty (or nearly empty) tank. After approximately 20 minutes, the driver observed acid overflowing from the scrubber tank and in an effort to keep additional acid from spilling into the containment area, he closed one of two in-line valves on the vent lines from the acid tank to the scrubber instead of shutting off flow at the tank. Shortly after closing the vent valve, the operator heard a muffled explosion and the bottom of the tank being filled ruptured at the lower head, releasing acid into the containment area. While the majority of acid was confined within the containment, an unknown portion (50-100 gallons) escaped containment and impacted an approximately 10 square yard area on an adjacent property owned by the lease owner.  Following the tank rupture and release, the driver shut down the transfer pumps and contacted dispatch, who then contacted RSI. RSI dispatched several personnel from the Cuero and Pleasanton yards to the site for initial assistance, as well as a spill response contractor (Mr. Eddie Lero with Cleaning Solutions of Bryan, TX). In addition, RSI personnel began searching for a lined vacuum truck capable of removing acid from the containment. Once on-scene, RSI personnel applied soda ash to the material outside of containment to limit life and property damage. By 11:00 the release of product from both the delivery trailer and the tank had ceased. Product recovery operations using an acid-rated vacuum truck began at approximately 13:00 but were terminated a
column169: As a result of this incident, Reagent Chemical and RSI have proposed the following corrective/preventative actions:    1. The practice of unsupervised bulk HCl deliveries will no longer be permitted. RSI will provide an attendant familiar with the site to supervise bulk acid deliveries.    2. Additional signage will be placed at site (on tanks, valves, etc.) clarifying tank and valve nomenclature and providing simplified off-loading instructions, as well as an RSI contact number for assistance.    3. Special instructions will be added to the Bill of Lading (BOL) that require driver/dispatch to contact RSI in the event of a question concerning tank selection or for any other question related to material transfer at the Cotulla facility.    4. The practice of placing additional valves in vent line will be reviewed to see if vent lines can be re-designed without them.    5. A design evaluation of the current scrubber system will be made to confirm that vent pipe sizing and head pressure of water scrubber does not exceed MAWP for tank. Delivery drivers will instructed to off-load at a controlled, slow rate to reduce the likelihood of an overpressure.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: During offloading of a van trailer, the facility personnel noticed a small leak on a super sack style IBC. Crew immediately notified management. An in house emergency response team was dispatched. In proper personal protective equipment, the facility personnel safely moved the pallet and sack into containment. ER team arrived on site, donned the proper PPE and assessed the site and trailer. It was determined that the pallet on to which the IBC  was loaded, had broken and pierced the container. Only the pallet and trailer were impacted by the release; no soil, water, or storm drains were impacted. The ER team thoroughly decontaminated the trailer. The waste generated from the clean-up, along with the waste from the super sack were repackaged into the appropriate UN spec 55-gallon drums, labeled and marked appropriately and sent to their final disposal destination without further incident.  The Texas Commission of Environmental Quality was notified at 10:00 CST and report #20172253 was assigned to the incident.

column168: AT 16:23 HRS ON 7/22/17, IT WAS REPORTED THAT RAILCAR RTMX 13064 WAS SLOSHING FROM THE MANWAY COVER AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAYS SHREVEPORT YARD. THE ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO ASSESS AND SECURE THE PACKAGE. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND ALL MANWAY SWING BOLTS UNHINGED. THE CONTRACTOR SECURED THE MANWAY BY TIGHTENING THE SWING BOLTS TOOL TIGHT. THE REMAINING CLOSURES WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A ‘BULK’ SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASE (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. column168: AT 11:56 HRS ON 7/28/2017, AN ODOR WITH AN UNIDENTIFIABLE ORIGIN WAS REPORTED AT THE SOUTH END OF THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) SHREVEPORT YARD. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DEPLOYED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE YARD TO INVESTIGATE. AT 14:00 HRS, THE SMELL WAS TRACED TO THE RAIL-CAR WCHX 23126 CONTAINING HAZMAT (UN1299) TURPENTINE. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT THE MAN-WAY NOZZLE GASKET WAS ROLLED ON THE EDGE AND WAS NOT IN THE CORRECT POSITION. ADDITIONALLY, ONE OF THE MAN-WAY BOLTS WAS HANGING FREELY. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ESTIMATED THAT ½ GALLON WAS RELEASED FROM THE MAN-WAY.   THE GASKET WAS POSITIONED IN THE CORRECT POSITION AND ALL MAN-WAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT. THE RESIDE WAS WIPED DOWN FROM THE CAR AND THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION. column168: ON THE MORNING OF JULY 1, 2017 OUR COMPANY DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO LOAD 4,950 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC AT SPRAGUE ENERGY TERMINAL. IT WAS ROUGHLY 4:30AM WHEN THE DRIVER STARTED TO LOAD. IT WAS DARK OUTSIDE. THE LOADING RACK HAS LIGHTS BUT THEY CAUSE SHADOWS IN AN UNLOADED TRAILER AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. THE DRIVER DID NOT VERIFY THAT THE TANK WAS COMPLETELY EMPTY FROM THE PREVIOUS LOAD. DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, THE DRIVER WAS NOT PAYING ATTENTION TO THE TANK LEVEL, HE WAS ONLY WATCHING THE METER. UPON WATCHING THE METER LEVEL COME CLOSE TO THE ORDERED AMOUNT, THE DRIVER SHUT THE PUMP OFF AT 4,957 GALLONS, WHICH IN TURN FILLED THE TANK TOO FULL. PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE MANHOLE AND FLOWED DOWN THE MOAT DRAIN TUBES. THE PRODUCT THAT HIT THE GROUND IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS. THE TERMINAL PERSONNEL ALONG WITH THE DRIVER, CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. AS YOU CAN SEE, THIS WAS NOT EQUIPMENT OR TANK FAILURE. THE WAS HUMAN ERROR.
column169: I HAVE ADVISED ALL OF OUR DRIVES TO VERIFY ALL TANKS ARE COMPLETELY EMPTY PRIOR TO LOADING.

column168: PALLET OF DAYTON SUPERIOR J35 TUF SEAL WAS PUT ON 20’ FLATBED. THE PALLET WAS CENTERED ON THE BED. IT WAS TIGHT AGAINST THE HEADACHE RACK. THE PALLET CONTAINED 36 EACH 5 GAL. BUCKETS OF DAYTON SUPERIOR J35 TUF SEAL. THE PALLET WAS SHRINK WRAPPED. ONE 2” STRAP WAS PLACED OVER THE TOP, CENTERED ON THE MIDDLE CANS.   THE TRUCK WAS HEADING NORTH ON GARDEN. WHEN TURNING EAST ONTO PARK DRIVE THE PALLET SHIFTED. FIVE CANS FELL ONTO ROAD WAY. TRUCK DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE CANS UPRIGHT SO THEY WOULD NOT LEAK ONTO ROADWAY. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND PUT KITTY LITTER ON THE SPILL. STONEWAY’S SPILL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AND ALSO PUT KITTY LITTER ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL RAN INTO THE STORM DRAIN. STONEWAY DRIVER MADE A DAM OUT OF SAND AND KITTY LITTER TO STOP FLOW.

ADDITIONAL ON BANDING AROUND AND OVER LAYERS OF PAILS TO PREVENT SHIFTING ON PALLET.  4.  SUPERVISOR WILL DOUBLE CHECK ALL LOADS GOING OUT FOR DELIVERY TO ENSURE PROPER STRAPPING TECHNIQUES AND PLACEMENT.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: The actual incident occurred on 7/11/17. Facility management failed to notify Transportation Compliance until 9/1/17. The container was a wrangler Bag on a wooden pallet. The pallet appeared to have been damaged allowing the weight of the bag to force a portion of itself through the opening. The bag was punctured by the damaged pallet creating a release of free liquid liberated from the contained material during transport. A Management Team Investigation was held on 9/5/17 to determine how the failure to properly report a hazardous release occurred. It was found that the facility manager misclassified the release as not in transit and failed to make the proper notifications. The manager has been re-trained and instructed to re-train all facility personnel in proper reporting procedures and hierarchy
column169: Facility management has been re-trained as to what constitutes an in-transit release. Facility management has been further instructed to re-train all facility personnel in proper incident reporting and hierarchy.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Valve Open
column168: Tank car DBCX 625 was reported to be leaking.  Inspection of car revealed the liquid ball valve to be half open and the plug in position, not wrench tight.  The vapor ball valve 4 bolt flange was also noted leaking around the flange connection.  Upon closing the liquid valve, tightening the liquid valve plug, and 4 vapor valve flange nuts; the car was secure from further leakage.  Upon securement the car was released to continue in transportation with no remediation required due to product evaporation. Combination housing cable seal BASF A2304939 was replaced with new seal BASF A2304944.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: THE FUEL RELEASE OCCURRED ON JULY 4, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 P.M. THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE 8,000 GALLON CAPACITY FUEL TANKER ROLLING OVER ONTO A METAL TRASH DUMPSTER LOCATED ADJACENT THE SOUTHWEST CORNER OF THE DOGWALK MARKET BUILDING. AS THE TRACTOR TRAILER ENTERED THE SOUTHWEST ENTRANCE TO THE FACILITY, FOR THE OFF LOADING OF FUEL INTO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST) SYSTEM, THE REAR WHEELS OR THE TANKER SLIPPED DOWN THE OUT SLOPE OF A GRASSY EMBANKMENT, THUS CAUSING THE TANKER TO ROLL OVER AND ONTO THE DUMPSTER. THE CORNER OF THE DUMPSTER RUPTURED ONE (1) OF THE ALUMINUM COMPARTMENT OF THE TANKER AND RELEASED FUEL ON THE GRASS AND GRAVEL SURFACES. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT THE RELEASE OF FUEL OCCURRED FOR LESS THAN ONE MINUTE.     IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE RELEASE THE DUNNVILLE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT AND PULASKI COUNTY SPECIAL RESPONSE, KYEM HAZ-MAT 12 RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT AND PLACED ABSORBENT BOOMS AND PADS IN THE SPILL AREA.     THE REMAINING FUEL WAS PUMPED FROM THE TANKER INTO A TANK WAGON OWNED AND OPERATED BY KENTUCKY PETROLEUM SUPPLY. FUEL WAS ALSO OFF-LOADED FROM THE TANKER UTILIZING A VAC TRUCK. THE FUEL WAS PUMPED INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS LOCATED AT THE SITE. FOLLOWING THE PUMPING OF THE TANKER IT WAS LIFTED UPRIGHT USING TOW TRUCKS AND HAULED FROM THE SITE.  PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED DATA SHEETS AND PHOTOS.
column169: ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES INCLUDE THE CLOSING OF THE ENTRANCE WHERE THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AND AN EMPHASIS PLACED ON DRIVER AWARENESS, BEST PRACTICES, AND SAFETY.

column168: ON 7/27/2017 THE GATX 70049 WAS FOUND BY AN FRA INSPECTOR IN NEWCASTLE WY TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WITH RESIDUE ON THE SIDES. THE FRA INSPECTOR NOTIFIED THE BNSF TRANSPORTATION TEAM WHO ISOLATED THE CAR, MADE NOTIFICATIONS AND SENT A TRAINMASTER TO INSPECT THE CAR. THE TRAINMASTER ALSO NOTIFIED WYOMING REFINING IN NEWCASTLE WHO HAS LOADED AND SHIPPED THE CAR. WYOMING REFINING PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE CAR AND FOUND THAT A SMALL AMOUNT (<0.5 GALLONS) OF CLARIFIED OIL HAS RELEASED THROUGH THE MANWAY SEALING AREA. THEIR INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE LID GASKET HAD A DEFECT THAT ALLOWED PRODUCT TO PASS THROUGH THE SEALING AREA. THE OLD GASKET WAS REMOVED AND A NEW LID GASKET WAS INSTALLED IN PLACED. WYOMING REFINING CLEANED THE CAR AND NOTED THAT NO PRODUCT HAD IMPACTED THE GROUND. THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION ONCE BNSF TRAINMASTER CLEARED THE AREA
column169: THE SHIPPER IS AWARE OF THE ISSUES LEADING UP TO THE NON-ACCIDENTAL RELEASE. POLICIES AND PROCEDURES SHOULD BE REVIEWED TO ENSURE THE TANK CAR SECUREMENTS. GASKETS AND APPLIANCES ARE ALL PROPERLY INSPECTED BEFORE RELEASING THE CAR INTO TRANSPORTATION

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A VEHICLE ROLLOVER CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE TANK TRUCK, WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 5,000 GALLONS OF JET FUEL. THE FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY, SHOULDER EMBANKMENT, AND SOIL WITHIN THE MEDIAN. REPUBLIC CARRIERS DISPATCHED A RECOVERY TANKER TO PUMP REMAINING FUEL FROM DAMAGED TANK. KIOWA COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT AND OKLAHOMA HIGHWAY PATROL RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION SPECIALISTS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, FREE LIQUID WAS DETECTED WITHIN THE SOIL EMBANKMENT AND SOIL MEDIAN. ERS UTILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER FREE PRODUCT FROM AFFECTED AREAS, DEPLOYED ABSORBENT BOOM TO PREVENT MIGRATION, AND ASSISTED IN CLEARING THE ROADWAY. CONTINUOUS FREE PRODUCT RECOVERY AND SOIL EXCAVATION WERE PERFORMED BY ERS UNTIL ALL CONTAMINATION WAS RECOVERED. THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO STATE WATERS AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.
column169: REPUBLIC CARRIERS WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: TRUCK WAS TRAVELING AT 6 MPH ON A DIRT ROAD AND DRIFTED ONTO THE SOFT DIRT SHOULDER, FRONT STEER TIRE SANK INTO THE SOFT DIRT. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT AND RETURN ONTO THE ROADWAY AND WAS UNABLE TO DO SO. THE VEHICLE CONTINUED TO SLIDE DOWN THE DIRT EMBANKMENT. AS THE WEIGHT OF THE LOAD SHIFTED IT PULLED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ONTO IT’S SIDE. THE TANK TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED BY “T” POST FENCING IN FOUR PLACES. PRODUCT WAS LEAKING VERY SLOWLY FROM TWO SMALL HOLES WHICH ALLOWED THE RELEASE TO BE CONTAIN UNTIL OUR CLEAN UP SERVICES ARRIVED. PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE PUNCTURED TANK TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED ONTO ANOTHER TRUCK. SOIL CONTAMINATED FROM THE RELEASE WAS REMOVED UNDER SUPERVISION BY BAKERSFIELD CERTIFIED UNIFIED PROGRAM AGENCY, AND SENT OUT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: OPERATING PROCEDURE AWARENESS WAS DISCUSSED WITH ALL DRIVERS WITH A FOCUS ON DISTRACTED DRIVING. SMITH SYSTEM DEFENSIVE DRIVING COURSE IS ONGOING AND WE WILL CONTINUE TRAINING TO ENSURE ALL DRIVERS UNDERSTAND CAUSE AND PREVENTION OF THESE TYPES OF INCIDENTS. DUE TO THE SEVERITY OF THIS INCIDENT WORLD OIL TRANSFER HAS CHOSEN TO RELEASE THIS DRIVER FROM FURTHER EMPLOYMENT.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED TO UNLOAD INTO ABOVE GROUND TANK. MECHANIC ON SITE TOLD HIM THERE WAS 5.6” IN THE TANK AND IT SHOULD HOLD HIS LOAD. HE STARTED PUMPING INTO THE TANK. ON THE LAST COMPARTMENT IN THE TRUCK TO UNLOAD, THE DRIVER STARTED PUMPING, WALKED AWAY ABOUT 80 YARDS TO THE SHOP. WALKED BACK AFTER 3 MINUTES AND FOUND THE TANK SPILLING OVER. DRIVER AND SUPERVISOR BEGAN IMMEDIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES.
column169: WE PROVIDED FURTHER TRAINING AND INSTRUCTIONS TO ALL OF OUR DRIVERS ON OUR MANDATORY RULES + PROCEDURE TO NEVER WALK AWAY FROM UNLOADING OPERATIONS AND REMINDED THEM OF STRICT ENFORCEMENT AND CONSEQUENCES REGARDING THESE PROCEDURES. ALSO OUR STRICT POLICIES AND PROCEDURES ON ENSURING BY USING DIGITAL SYSTEM AS WELL AS MANUAL STICKING THAT TANKS WILL HOLD FUEL.

column43: KIT LIS 02 LITHIUM BATTERY REPLACEMENT ASSEMBLY CAT #: 11141-000148
column168: AT 09:30 AM EDT ON 10 JULY 2017 NET JEST SALES INC LOACTED AT 4111 BRIDGEWAY AVE COLUMBUS OHIO 43219 RECEIVED A UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT OF A CLASS 9 UN3090 LITHIUM METAL BATTEREIS (3) IN A OVERPACKED BOX FROM EXECUTIVE JET MANAGEMENT INC PARTS DEPARTMENT 38 LOOP ROAD WHITE PLAINS NY 10604. THE BOX WAS SHIPPE DBY AIR ON FEDEX AIRWAY BILL 4511 5995 9003 AND WAS NOT DECLARED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR OUTER SHIPPING BOX MARKED AS HAZARODUS MATERIAL. THE INNER PACKAGING WAS MARKED AS OVERPACK UN3090 LITHIUM METAL BATTEREIS AND CONTINED 3 BATTERIS IN ORGINAL PACKAGING. EXECUTIVE JET MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED ON 11 JULY 2017 AND STARTED AN INVESTIGATION. THE INDIVIDUAL THAT SHIPPED THE BOX WAS NOT AVAILABLE TO BE INTERVIEWED DUE TO BEING ON MEDICAL LEAVE WITH AN UNDETERMINED RETURN DATE. THE INDIVIDUAL WAS PROPERLY TRAINED AND AUTHORIZED BY EXECUTIVE JET MANAGEMENT, INC TO CONDUCT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS ON BEHALF OF EXECUTIVE JET MANAGEMENT, INC HIS LAST HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPER TRAINING CLASS WAS COMPLETED ON OCTOBER 31 2016, HE HAD NO PRIOR HISTORY OF VIOLATING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING REGULATIONS WHILE SERVING AS AN EMPLOYEEE OF EXECUTIVE JET MANAGEMENT.
column169: The shipper was properly trained, current and had all required materials and references available to completed thisshipment in accordance to hazardous material regulations. He had no prior history of violating the hazardousmaterials shipping laws.Until the shipper can be interviewed to determine a root cause of his actions no recommendations can be provided.Due to his personal medical situation, we do not know if he will ever be able to return to work and become availablefor the interview.

column168: CUSTOMER ORDER 150 GAL, INVOICE # 17085105 81.3 GAL   DURING RESIDENTIAL HOME HEATING OIL DELIVERY. #2 LS DYED DIESEL.  WISTLE/VENT ALARM WAS MAKING AN AUDIBLE WISTLE.    TANK OVERFILLED AND LEAKING FROM VENT, DOWN SIDING INTO PLANTER SOIL.  I IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF FILL VALVE 1 T O1.5 SECONDS AS I WAS AT THE NOZZLE.  WENT TO TRUCK, SHUT OFF THE METER, SHUT OFF THE PTO, AND SHUT OFF THE TRUCK.  THERE WAS NO RISK TO PASSING CARS, OR PEDESTRIANS AS THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED AT THE HOUSE.    SO NO EMERGENCY CALLS WERE MADE. GRABBED ABSORBENT PADS. CONTAINED EXTERIOR SPILL.   KNOCKED ON THE DOOR TO ALERT THE CUSTOMER OF THE SPILL AND GAIN ACCESS TO GARAGE TANK AREA.     TANK WAS WEEPING OIL FROM THE FITTING AT TOP OF TANK, I INSISTED THAT HE NOT TOUCH THE TANK OR FITTING AS IT WILL CREATE A LARGER SPILL.  I CAREFULLY REMOVED THE FILL VALVE AND HOSE, OIL LEVEL BELOW FILL PIPE. ADVISED CUSTOMER TO START THE HEATING SYSTEM TO DRAW THE OIL LEVEL DOWN, AS SOON AS THE LEVEL WAS LOWERED I WAS ABLE TO REMOVE THE CAPS TO VERIFY LEVEL, RETURNED CAP AND TIGHTENED.    GOT SPILL KIT WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP SPILL.  REMOVED SATURATED SOIL AND PLACED ALL CONTAMINATED PADS IN A HOME DEPOT BUCKET PROVIDE BY THE CUSTOMER.    CUSTOMER INSISTED ON DISPOSAL OF THE SPILL MATERIALS AND SOIL, I INFORMED HIM I NEED TO REPORT THE SPILL. HE WAS VERY ADAMANT HE DID NOT WANT ME TO REPORT IT. NOTE: (FOLLOWED JONES OIL LLC SPILL PROCEDURE)
column169: RECOMMENDATION:  SOMETHING IN THE VENT PIPE WAS CAUSING THE WISTLE AS THE WISTLE ITSELF IF FAULTY.  THE VENT PIPE AND WISTLE NEED TO BE CLEANED AND OR REPLACED, AND INSPECTED PRIOR TO FURTHER DELIVERY.  PLACED ACCOUNT ON HOLD UNTIL LEVEL OF TANK DROPS SO REPAIRS CAN BE PERFORMED.   INSPECTION OF THE WISTLE WILL BE REQUIRED BEFORE ANY NEW DELIVERY REQUEST WILL BE SATISFIED.    NOTE: DURING CLEAN UP.  IN SPEAKING WITH THE CUSTOMER I LEARNED THAT THE FLOAT GAUGE WAS NOT WORKING AND SHOWS EMPTY.  HE STATED HE DIPPED THE TANK WITH A STICK AND IT SHOWED EMPTY. CLEARLY HE WAS MISTAKEN.   HE APOLOGIZED FOR ORDERING AS HE THOUGHT IT WOULD TAKE THE WHOLE 150 GALLON DELIVERY.  THE WISTLE ALERTS US TO THE TANK VENTING AND IT’S FULL MARK BUT THE VENT PIPE BEING DIRTY CREATED A WISTLE THROUGHOUT THE DURATION OF FILLING, CAUSING AN ACCIDENTAL SPILL.

column168: AT 13:00 HOURS ON JULY 31, 2017, RAILCARS BEING BROUGHT IN BY CENTRAL CALIFORNIA TRACTION COMPANY (CCT) COLLIDED WITH THE RAILCARS THAT WERE ALREADY ON PACIFIC ETHANOL’S INNER TRACK RESULTING IN THE CARS MOVING ONE (1) FULL CAR LENGTH IN DISTANCE. FOUR (4) RAILCARS WERE HOOKED UP TO THE 4 OFFLOADING STATIONS BUT WERE NOT ACTIVELY OFFLOADING WHEN THE COLLISION OCCURRED WHICH CAUSED ALL 4 HOSES TO BREAK AND RELEASE ETHANOL. BASED ON VISUAL OBSERVATIONS THE ORIGINAL ESTIMATE OF RELEASE WAS 2,000 GALLONS, THEN UPON EXCAVATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 7,000 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.  THE TIME OF THE COLLISION TO THE TIME THE VALVES UNDER THE RAILCARS WERE CLOSED WAS LESS THAN 5 MINUTES. NRC WAS CONTACTED THE SAME DAY OF THE SPILL AND ARRIVED ON SITE THE FOLLOWING DAY (AUGUST 1, 2017) TO IMMEDIATELY EXCAVATE CONTAMINATED SOIL. EXCAVATION WAS COMPLETED ON AUGUST 18, 2017. IMPACTED SOIL WAS CONCENTRATED MOSTLY AT THE FRONT OF THE 4 RAILCARS, DUE TO THAT CAR BEING PUSHED PAST THE FACILITY’S RAILCAR CONTAINMENT  BACKFILL WAS APPROVED BY THE WATERBOARD ON SEPTEMBER 15, 2017 FOLLOWING SUBMISSION OF A NO FURTHER ACTION (NFA) REQUEST.  BACKFILL WAS COMPLETED ON SEPTEMBER 29, 2017
column169: PROCEDURES HAVE CHANGED BETWEEN CCT AND PACIFIC ETHANOL. NO RAIL-CARS WILL BE ALLOWED TO ENTER THE FACILITY’S TRACK UNLESS ALL CARS ARE UNHOOKED AND ADDITIONALLY LOCKED IN PLACE.   THE FACILITY HAS PURCHASED PORTABLE DERAILS TO FURTHER PROTECT ANY CARS ON THE FACILITY’S TRACK WHEN ADDITIONAL CARS ARE BEING BROUGHT ON SITE.  SOP’S HAVE BEEN UPDATED FOR ALLOWING ADDITIONAL CARS ON SITE, AND WILL BE FURTHER UPDATED ONCE THE PORTABLE DERAILS ARRIVE. CCT HAS BEEN INFORMED OF THE NEW PROCEDURES AND HAVE AGREED TO FOLLOW THEM AS WELL

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED INTACT, WITH NO RELEASE OR DAMAGE, AT THE RECIPIENT FACILITY (GENERAL DYNAMICS). THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE HAD THE FEDEX GROUND SHIPPING LABEL. THE PACKING LIST WAS INSIDE THE OUTER BOX. THE INNER BOX WAS INTACT AND CONTAINED 8EA OF GD PART NUMBER SK55402-101 (RCS PART 8223AL, 1%, 1.308 OD, 1.213 ID).THESE PARTS WERE INDIVIDUALLY PACKAGED INTO SEALED ANTI-STATIC BAGS. THE GD MATERIAL HANDLER NOTICED THE PART NUMBER/DESCRIPTION ON THE PURCHASE ORDER DID NOT MATCH THE PACKING LIST. THE GD PART NUMBER WAS FOR AN ENERGETIC ITEM. THE MATERIAL HANDLER CONTACTED THE GD PURCHASING DEPARTMENT TO GET CLARIFICATION. GD PURCHASING CONTACTED RCS AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ENCLOSED PACKING LIST DID NOT REFERENCE THE CORRECT MATERIAL. RCS EMAILED A CORRECTED PACKING LIST AND THE MATERIAL WAS ROUTED TO GD MAGAZINE FOR PROPER STORAGE. GD SENT A LETTER TO RCS ON8/15/2017 INFORMING THEM IN WRITING ON WHAT HAD OCCURRED AND AN EXPECTATION FOR CORRECTION OF THE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT. RCS SENT A REPLY LETTER ON 8/22/2017 EXPLAINING WHAT HAD OCCURRED IN THEIR SYSTEM AND WHAT THEY ARE DOING TO CORRECT THE SITUATION.BOTH LETTERS ARE ATTACHED.
column169: IN RCS RESPONSE LETTER, THEY STATED THEY HAVE A PROTOCOL IN PLACE TO ENSURE THIS MISTAKE DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. INTERNALLY AT GENERAL DYNAMICS WE HAVE DISCUSSED THE INCIDENT WITH ALL OF OUR MATERIAL HANDLER PERSONNEL AND LOCAL MANAGEMENT TEAMS.
